In the mixins.database, the get_options method does not check the upper+lower combinations: we do an «upper» in the key checking and not during the split so a «database_options» would not match the split.

This should be easy to fix but I set the issue to do it later.

```python
# django-kaio/kaio/mixins/database.py
    def get_options(self):
        options = {}
        for key in opts.keys():
            if 'DATABASE_OPTIONS_' in key.upper():
                options[str(key.split('DATABASE_OPTIONS_')[1].lower())] = get(key)
        return options
```

It's not obvious from the docs at https://mana.mozilla.org/wiki/display/CLOUDSERVICES/Logging+Standard, but we don't support recursive fields in our logging standard (because protobuf does not support them). In the case where the app has such structured fields, we need them to be serialized as nested JSON strings, e.g.

    {..., "Fields":{"querystring": {"foo": "bar"}}}

should instead be serialized as:

    {..., "Fields":{"querystring": "{\"foo\": \"bar\"}"}}

The JSON schema is here: https://mana.mozilla.org/wiki/pages/viewpage.action?pageId=42895640

[A change](https://github.com/zopefoundation/ZConfig/commit/010cb2b2d4d2cdc8cd327f9f46a987024cac5b67#diff-bd559d1f48a7d2df54fca55965db90b2R223) in ZConfig 3.2.0 leads to socket binding addresses being text on both Python2 and Python3.

This breaks runzeo.py's [`ZEOServer.clear_socket` method](https://github.com/zopefoundation/ZEO/blob/master/src/ZEO/runzeo.py#L196) (on Python 2) which only removes the socket file if it is the type of a string literal:
```python

def clear_socket(self):
  if isinstance(self.options.address, type("")):
     try:
        os.unlink(...)
```

Under Python 2, the string literal is a `bytes` object, not a text object.

Now, this wasn't a documented ZConfig change and it wasn't even exactly intended (it was the result of consistency improvements between the behaviour of Python 2 and Python 3, plus bug fixes). Still, because this project already has a dependency on `six`, it seems to make sense to use `six.string_types` there instead of `type("")`, which would solve the issue.

