Looking at `RecordProcessor::process_records`

```
    def process_records(self, process_records_input):
        ...
        try:
            for record in process_records_input.records:
                ...

        except Exception as e:
            sys.stderr.write("Encountered an exception while processing records. Exception was {e}\n".format(e=e))
```

I see that any exception raised in the `try` block will be written to stderr. However, the stderr buffer is not flushed immediately. In consequence, error messages are not displayed in the MultiLangDaemon's stdout, making debugging harder.

In your opinion, what would be the best solution to this problem? Here are some ideas:

- [disable output buffering](https://docs.python.org/2/using/cmdline.html#cmdoption-u) (`executableName = python -u myscript.py`)
- modify `RecordProcessor` so that it uses `amazon_kclpy.kcl._IOHandler`, e.g.:
```
    def process_records(self, process_records_input):
        ...
        try:
            for record in process_records_input.records:
                ...

        except Exception as e:
            # self.iohandler would have to be injected somewhere
            self.iohandler.write_error("Encountered an exception while processing records. Exception was {e}\n".format(e=e))
```
- handle exceptions myself from `MyCustomRecordProcessor` at the `process_record` level:
```
logger = logging.getLogger()
class MyCustomRecordProcessor(RecordProcessor):
    def process_record(self, data, partition_key, sequence_number, sub_sequence_number):
        try:
            # some exception is raised here
        except as e:
            logger.error("Something wrong happened: {e}".format(e=e))
```

I think I've seen this page before, but we haven't had to deal with it yet:

![screen shot 2018-02-23 at 22 19 44](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/236970/36626450-c7f9d2a4-18e7-11e8-977c-a0ca3d45c6a0.png)

I just ran into this at [CAED][1]. From what I can tell, larger dockets trigger this, and the trick is to:

1. Detect that we've hit this page instead of loading a docket. This can probably be done by parsing the page. The URL of the page screenshotted above is:

        https://ecf.caed.uscourts.gov/cgi-bin/DktRpt.pl?109773342314839-L_1_0-1

    A normal page is basically the same:

        https://ecf.caed.uscourts.gov/cgi-bin/DktRpt.pl?421893294267327-L_1_1-1

    Hm. But that second boolean at the end of flipped to `1` on a normal docket. Hm, a clue.

1. Grab the action URL from the HTML in this case:

        <form enctype="multipart/form-data" method="POST" action="../cgi-bin/DktRpt.pl?421893294267327-L_1_1-1">

2. Submit the form sending the param `date_from` with no value (or with an empty string).

3. Profit?

Here's the full HTML (whitespace cleaned up):

```
    <form enctype="multipart/form-data" method="POST" action="../cgi-bin/DktRpt.pl?421893294267327-L_1_1-1">
			<input name="date_from" value="02/16/2018" checked="" type="radio"> for the past week<br>
			<input name="date_from" value="11/25/2017" type="radio"> for the past 90 days<br>
			<input name="date_from" value="02/23/2017" type="radio"> for the past year<br>
			<input name="date_from" value="" type="radio"> as initially requested<br>
		</p>
	<script language="JavaScript">
		var timerId;
		var BeenHere = 0;
		IsForm  = true;
		function empty(s) {
			var whitespace = " \t\n\r";
			if(s == null || s.length == 0) {
				return(true);
			}
		    // Is s only whitespace characters?
		    for (var i = 0; i < s.length; i++) {
		        var c = s.charAt(i);
       			 if (whitespace.indexOf(c) == -1) return false;
		    }
